    <item>
      <title>The Grid, Inherited</title>
      <link>https://tor2dbear.github.io/portfolio/preview/claude/css-testing-strategy-e7DmS/writing/the-grid-inherited/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://tor2dbear.github.io/portfolio/preview/claude/css-testing-strategy-e7DmS/writing/the-grid-inherited/</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 11 May 2026 00:00:00 &#43;0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Printed design rests on a grid that is almost invisible to the reader but impossible to do without as a designer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Josef Müller-Brockmann&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;Grid Systems in Graphic Design&lt;/em&gt; (1961) codified a system already embedded in centuries of typographic practice: columns, gutters, margins, and baselines coordinating every element on the page. The grid is not a constraint but a promise — that the composition holds together, that its elements exist in relation to one another, that the structure beneath the surface remains coherent even as the content changes.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The Page Unprinted</title>
      <link>https://tor2dbear.github.io/portfolio/preview/claude/css-testing-strategy-e7DmS/the-page-unprinted/the-page-unprinted/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://tor2dbear.github.io/portfolio/preview/claude/css-testing-strategy-e7DmS/the-page-unprinted/the-page-unprinted/</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 11 May 2026 00:00:00 &#43;0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s something poetic about print. A PDF is a promise—a fixed moment, a document that won&amp;rsquo;t reflow or rerender. Yet the web, built for screens, treats print as an afterthought.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;The Gap Between Screen and Page&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When I set out to create print-ready exports for my portfolio, I expected CSS to handle it gracefully. After all, we have &lt;code&gt;@media print&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;@page&lt;/code&gt; rules, and break properties. The specification exists. The reality is messier.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
